### Simple plots
Display the evolution of the French Life Expectancy over the years in a **bar chart**.

from pyspark.sql import functions as F

df = px.data.gapminder()


df_france = df.query("country == 'France'")

first_bar_object = px.bar(df_france,
    x='year', 
    y='pop', 
    title="Evolution population en France",
    text ='year'
)
first_bar_object.update_traces(marker_color='#90EE90')

first_bar_object.show()

#your code here
Let's repeat the process, but this time we will display the evolution of Life Expectancy for France, Germany and Poland.

<u>Additional requirements :</u>


- Display three bars for each year, each representing a different country and using distinct colors.
- Make sure that the three bars are separate and not stacked.
<details>
    <summary> Hint üîç </summary>

Have a look at the Dataframe `.isin()`method to filter on more than one value

</details>
#your code hereimport plotly.express as px

# Load the gapminder dataset
df = px.data.gapminder()

# Filter the data for France, Germany, and Poland
df_selected = df[df['country'].isin(['France', 'Germany', 'Japan'])]

# Create a grouped bar chart with distinct colors for each country
bar_chart_countries = px.bar(df_selected, x='year', y='lifeExp', color='country', barmode='group',
                             title='Evolution of Life Expectancy for France, Germany, and Poland')

# Customize the colors for each country
bar_chart_countries.update_traces(marker_line_color='rgb(8,48,107)', marker_line_width=1.5, opacity=0.6)

# Show the grouped bar chart
bar_chart_countries.show()
Bar charts might not the best suited type of representation. \
Modify the previous code to represent the evolution of Life Expectancy with a **line chart**. Does it look better ?
import plotly.express as px

# Load the gapminder dataset
df = px.data.gapminder()

# Filter the data for France, Germany, and Poland
df_selected = df[df['country'].isin(['France', 'Germany', 'Poland'])]

# Create a line chart for the evolution of life expectancy
line_chart_countries = px.line(df_selected, x='year', y='lifeExp', color='country',
                               title='Evolution of Life Expectancy for France, Germany, and Poland')

# Show the line chart
line_chart_countries.show()
### Complex plots
We can use additional parameters like sizes and colors to add more information to our graphs.

For the year 2007, visualize the relationship between the GDP per capita and the life expectancy. \
Think about the best type of graph to visualise correlations.

<u>Additional requirements:</u>

- Countries should be representated with different colors based on their continent
- Each country should have a different size proportional to its population
<u>Note:</u> the argument `size_max` can be set to 60 to increase the size of the data points while keeping the same proportions.
import plotly.express as px

# Charger le jeu de donn√©es gapminder
df = px.data.gapminder()

# Filtrer les donn√©es pour l'ann√©e 2007
df_2007 = df[df['year'] == 2007]

# Cr√©er un nuage de points pour visualiser la relation entre le PIB par habitant, l'esp√©rance de vie, la population et la couleur du continent
scatter_plot = px.scatter(df_2007, x='gdpPercap', y='lifeExp', size='pop', color='continent', hover_name='country',
                          title='Relation entre le PIB par habitant et l\'esp√©rance de vie (2007)',
                          labels={'gdpPercap': 'PIB par habitant', 'lifeExp': 'Esp√©rance de vie'},
                          size_max=60)

# Afficher le nuage de points
scatter_plot.show()

Each data point shows a lot of information, but unfortunately  we're missing the country name. \
Have a look at the [documentation](https://plotly.com/python-api-reference/generated/plotly.express.scatter.html) and find out how to add the country name when hovering over a circle with the mouse.
#your code here
What if we wanted to represent the same information for all the years and not only 2007 ?

We can do so by adding the time dimension to our graph, by creating an **animation**. \
Look at the documentation and find out how to include the year as an animation parameter. \
Make sure to pass the entire dataframe and not just the one from 2007.

<u>Note:</u> The axis limits are calculated for the first year by default. You can specify a fixed window using the `range_x` and `range_y` arguments.
import plotly.express as px

# Load the gapminder dataset
df = px.data.gapminder()

# Create a scatter plot with animation for the relationship between GDP per capita, life expectancy, and population over the years
scatter_animation = px.scatter(df, x='gdpPercap', y='lifeExp', size='pop', color='continent', hover_name='country',
                               animation_frame='year', animation_group='country',
                               title='Relationship between GDP per Capita and Life Expectancy over the Years',
                               labels={'gdpPercap': 'GDP per Capita', 'lifeExp': 'Life Expectancy'},
                               size_max=60, range_x=[100,70000], range_y=[25,90])

# Show the scatter plot with animation
scatter_animation.show()
